@kelleyflanagan from @bachelorabc recently came on a new journey restoring coral reefs with us! Watch to see the most dramatic Coral Restoration Foundation™ dive program yet!
You can start your coral restoration journey too! Sign up for one of our weekly Dive Programs and be the change! 🔗➡️📖
.
🎥: @alexander_neufeld_photo /Coral Restoration Foundation

Our team spends almost 2,000⏳hours every year battling biofoul. If we could reduce the time it takes to clean our Coral Trees, we could return more corals to the reef every year! 🎉
.
This is a chance for students to show off their engineering and design skills, and make a huge impact for corals! 
.
The winning students will receive a state-of-the-art educational aquarium for their school, from @titanaquaticexhibits 🐠🐡🐟
.

node.text:
Despite this year’s challenges, our team at Coral Restoration Foundation™ has worked nonstop to move our mission forward every single day.
.
Today our Restoration Program Coordinator, and boulder coral aficionado, Dan Burdeno, offers a look into his effort to #Restore2020 with CRF™. We hope Dan’s perspective will inspire you to help us turn this year right-side up, one coral at a time!
.
Every dollar donated to our restoration efforts on #GivingTuesday will be doubled by a generous donor who has pledged to match up to $20,000! This means that all gifts given ‪on December 1‬, will go twice as far in supporting our mission to restore coral reefs.
.
Coral reefs need your help now more than ever. Will you help us #Restore2020 ?
.
📹 : Maria McCausland/Coral Restoration Foundation™

.
Brianna, one of our recent dive program participants, put together this awesome video taking us through her entire day on a CRF™ Dive Program, from learning about the importance of coral reefs to getting out on the water and actively restoring our reef ecosystem.

If you've ever wondered what a CRF™ Dive Program is like, this is the video to watch 😍
.
You can also visit our website, coralrestoration.org/dive-programs to learn more 🤿
.
A big thank you to @bpatricew for creating this video and for helping us restore Florida's Coral Reef!
.

Only a few days until the submission deadline for the National Coral to Action Challenge! All entries must be received by Coral Restoration Foundation™ by 11:59 pm on Tuesday, February 11, 2020.
.
CRF™ is searching for a student film of one minute or less that best tells the world about the crisis facing our coral reefs and how people can help.
.
The winning film will be aired on the NBC 6 network, the “Coral to Action” Broadcast Sponsor! Together, we are giving America’s students an opportunity to amplify their message to save our planet’s coral reefs from extinction.
.
Learn more at coralrestoration.org/coral-to-action or visit our link in bio.

node.text:
Feeling under the weather? #FridayFieldUpdate is the cure!
.
Our Restoration Team has been busy training our interns to identify and treat coral disease! Coral diseases, bleaching, and stress responses present similar symptoms and it is important for our team to properly identify each in order to properly treat them. 
.
Disease identification wasn't the only test this week, our rising lead interns trained for their upcoming roll with professional leadership advice from our Education Team.
.
And just in case you missed it, we’ve been doing exciting work with @NOAA to sequencing the genes of all elkhorn corals in Florida and the Carribean. We think we have nearly 500, but it could be more!
.
We're never sitting still here! Next week, it's coral spawning!
.
📷 : Shane Gallimore/Coral Restoration Foundation™

node.text:
Porites, Oculina, & Favia, oh my!

These are just a handful of over 45 different coral species in the Florida Keys! Genetic diversity is hugely important to coral reefs as different species and genotypes react in various ways to bleaching,  acidic water, storms, nutrient levels, and diseases.

Our coral nurseries are home to over 480 unique coral genotypes across 11 species and that number is growing!

Here you see the diverse range of corals we rescued and relocated through our mitigation project with the Florida Keys Electric Co-Op. We keep them in our gene bank to preserve genetic diversity and will one day reintroduce them to the wild!

🎥: Tom Condon/Coral Restoration Foundation

node.text:
Just took a DNA test, turns out corals are 100% worth it. 
.
Our Science Team has launched an unprecedented coral gene sequencing project!
.
We are working with @noaa and restoration organizations throughout the Caribbean and Florida to sequence the genes of ALL 480 elkhorn corals currently studied by these groups. 
.
The data emerging from this effort will inform future restoration and management decisions and provide tremendous insight for future reef restoration!
.
You can read the first hand account of our team's work on this project in our weekly blog, The Coral Chronicles, linked in our bio!
.
This regional sequencing effort is made possible by funding from NOAA's Restoration Center. 
.
📷 : Coral Restoration Foundation™

node.text:
Can you spot our reef restoration audience member?? 👀
.
Sometimes we get surprise visits from reef animals curious about what we’re doing. In this 
video there is a very well camouflaged scorpion fish watching us return corals to their home, giving them even more places to hide! 
.
Scorpionfish are covered in sharp spines containing venom, yet another reason never to touch  the reef while diving for fun. Our team had a good eye and spotted this curious critter before we began our work! 
.
🎥:Sunny Siegel/Coral Restoration Foundation #scorpion #scorpionfish #camoflauge #coralrestorationfoundation #coralreef #coralreefs #reefrestoration #habitatrestoration #scubadiving #scuba #underwater #underwaterphotography

node.text:
#FridayFieldUpdate arriving just before the storm!
.
Tropical Storm Fred is on the horizon! Our team is spending the day securing our boats and warehouse and ensuring our Coral Nurseries are ship shape.
.
One of the major benefits of our Coral Tree™ design is their flexibility! They are able to flow with ocean currents without breaking away from their anchors, even during Cat 5 hurricanes, which we saw with Irma in 2017!
.
Earlier in the week we visited one of our favorite #Iconic reefs, Carysfort, and returned 400 staghorn corals to the wild. 
.
AND drumroll...coral spawning is predicted to be just one week away! You certainly won't want to miss this annual event! We can’t wait to see our corals become new parents!
.

node.text:
And that’s a wrap 🎬
.
At the end of our restoration dives we work as a team to put the 
finishing touches on the reef.
This includes wave testing all of the corals to make sure they are secure and cleaning up our 
tools.
.
Here you can also see one of our interns counting the corals in the cluster for monitoring purposes!
.
Of course we can’t forget about the most important thing at the end of the dive…saying 
goodbye to all of our fishy friends! 🐟🐠🐡
.

UPDATE: We are so happy to have such an involved group of people following our page thank you all for your thoughts! This photo does in fact show new growth! This is an Elkhorn coral (A. palmata) its tips appear white because the coral tissue and skeleton are growing very fast! The color of a coral comes from a symbiotic algae living inside the coral tissue. When corals grow quickly it takes some time for the algae to “move in” resulting in white tips! 
.
Good news for our corals, no bleaching here, they are just going through a growth spurt!
.
New growth or coral bleaching? Let us know what you think in the comments!

📷 : Shane Gallimore/Coral Restoration Foundation™
